# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biotechnology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] In one industrial chemical synthesis, acetylene reacts with two equivalents of formaldehyde to form butyne-1,4-diol.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] Hydrogenation of butyne-1,4-diol gives butane-1,4-diol.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] It is also made on an industrial scale from maleic anhydride in the Davy process, which is first converted to the methyl maleate ester, then hydrogenated.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] Other routes are from butadiene, allyl acetate and succinic acid.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] A biological route to BD has been commercialized that uses a genetically modified organism.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] The biosynthesis proceeds via 4-hydroxybutyrate.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is used industrially as a solvent and in the manufacture of some types of plastics, elastic fibers and polyurethanes.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] In organic chemistry, 1,4-butanediol is used for the synthesis of γ-butyrolactone (GBL).
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] In the presence of phosphoric acid and high temperature, it dehydrates to the important solvent tetrahydrofuran.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] At about 200 °C in the presence of soluble ruthenium catalysts, the diol undergoes dehydrogenation to form butyrolactone.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] It is used to synthesize 1,4-butanediol diglycidyl ether which is then used as a reactive diluent for epoxy resins.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] 1,4-Butanediol is used in the production of polybutylene terephthalate (PBT) plastic.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] World production of butane-1,4-diol was claimed to be about one million metric tons per year and market price is about US$2,000 (€1,600) per ton in 2005.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] In 2013, worldwide production was claimed to be billions of pounds (consistent with approximately one million metric tons).
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] Almost half of it is dehydrated to tetrahydrofuran to make fibers such as Spandex.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is also used as a recreational drug known by some users as "Bute", "One Comma Four", "Liquid Fantasy", "One Four Bee" or "One Four B-D-O".
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] Some federal courts in the United States have stated that 1,4-butanediol exerts effects similar to its metabolite, GABA analogue gamma-hydroxybutyrate (GHB), but several other federal courts have ruled that it does not.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] 1,4-but***e***nediol (CAS 110-64-5) may be incorrectly sold as 1,4-butanediol but should not be confused with it.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is rapidly converted into GHB acid by the enzymes alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase, and differing levels of these enzymes may account for differences in effects and side effects between users.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] While co-administration of ethanol and GHB already poses serious risks, co-administration of ethanol with 1,4-butanediol will interact considerably and has many other potential risks.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] This is because the same enzymes that are responsible for metabolizing alcohol also metabolize 1,4-butanediol so there is a strong chance of a dangerous drug interaction.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol seems to have two types of pharmacological actions.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] The major psychoactive effects of 1,4-butanediol are because it is metabolized into GHB; however there is a study suggesting that 1,4-butanediol may have potential alcohol-like pharmacological effects on its own.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] The study arrived at this conclusion based on the finding that butane-1,4-diol coadministered with ethanol led to potentiation of some of the behavioral effects of ethanol.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] However, potentiation of ethanol's effects may simply be caused by competition for the alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase enzymes with co-administered 1,4-butanediol.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] The shared metabolic rate-limiting steps thus leads to slowed metabolism and clearance for both compounds including ethanol's known toxic metabolite acetaldehyde.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] Another study found no effect following intracerebroventricular injection of butane-1,4-diol in rats.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] This contradicts the hypothesis of butane-1,4-diol having inherent alcohol-like pharmacological effects.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] Like gamma-hydroxybutyric acid, butane-1,4-diol is safe only in small amounts.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] Adverse effects in higher doses include nausea, vomiting, dizziness, sedation, vertigo, and potentially death if ingested in large amounts.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] Anxiolytic effects are diminished and side effects increased when used in combination with alcohol.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] While butane-1,4-diol is not currently scheduled federally in the United States, a number of states have classified 1,4-butanediol as a controlled substance.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] Individuals have been prosecuted for possession of 1,4-butanediol under the Federal Analog Act as substantially similar to GHB.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] A federal case in New York in 2002 ruled that 1,4-butanediol could not be considered an analog of GHB under federal law, but that decision was later overturned by the Second Circuit.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] A jury in Federal District Court in Chicago found that 1,4-butanediol was not an analog of GHB under federal law, which was not disputed on the case's appeal to the Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals, however this finding did not affect the outcome of the case.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] In the United Kingdom, 1,4-butanediol was scheduled in December 2009 (along with another GHB precursor, gamma-butyrolactone) as a Class C controlled substance.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] In Germany, the drug is not explicitly illegal, but might also be treated as illegal if used as a drug.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] It is controlled as a Schedule VI precursor in Canada.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] A toy called "Bindeez" ("Aqua Dots" in North America) was recalled by the distributor in November 2007 because of the presence of butane-1,4-diol.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] The toy consists of small beads that stick to each other by sprinkling water.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] The production plant seems to have intended to cut costs by replacing less toxic pentane-1,5-diol with butane-1,4-diol.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] ChemNet China listed the price of butane-1,4-diol at between about US$1,350–2,800 per metric ton, while the price for 1,5-pentanediol is about US$9,700 per metric ton.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] In August 2021, several people fell severely ill after consuming drinks at building L2.01 at the Lichtwiese Campus of Darmstadt Technical University, Germany.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] Seven showed severe symptoms, two were transported to a hospital in Frankfurt am Main, and a 30-year-old person was, for a time, in a critical state.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol had been detected in milk packages, as well as in water filters.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] At the location, detectives also found bromophenols and dicyclohexylamine.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] A variety of 1,4-butanediol derivatives are GHB-like drugs or GHB receptor agonists.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] These include GHB itself, γ-butyrolactone (GBL), aceburic acid, ethyl acetoxy butanoate (EAB), Γ-crotonolactone, γ-hydroxybutyraldehyde, γ-hydroxyvaleric acid (GHV), γ-valerolactone (GVL), γ-hydroxycrotonic acid (GHC or T-HCA), and 4-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoic acid (UMB68), among others.
[src:biotechnology/1-4-butanediol] An analogue that is not a 1,4-butanediol derivative but is related and still shows affinity for the GHB receptor is 3-chloropropanoic acid (UMB66).
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In livestock agriculture and the meat industry, a **slaughterhouse**, also called an **abattoir** (/ˈæbətwɑːr/ ⓘ), is a facility where livestock animals are slaughtered to provide food.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Slaughterhouses supply meat, which then becomes the responsibility of a meat-packing facility.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Slaughterhouses that produce meat that is not intended for human consumption are sometimes referred to as *knacker's yards* or *knackeries*.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] This is where animals are slaughtered that are not fit for human consumption or that can no longer work on a farm, such as retired work horses.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Slaughtering animals on a large scale poses significant issues in terms of logistics, animal welfare, and the environment, and the process must meet public health requirements.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Due to public aversion in different cultures, determining where to build slaughterhouses is also a matter of some consideration.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Frequently, animal rights groups raise concerns about the methods of transport to and from slaughterhouses, preparation prior to slaughter, animal herding, stunning methods, and the killing itself.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Until modern times, animals were slaughtered in a haphazard and unregulated manner in diverse places.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Early maps of London show numerous stockyards in the periphery of the city, where slaughter occurred in the open air or under cover such as wet markets.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Such open-air slaughterhouses were called *shambles*, and there are streets named "The Shambles" in some English and Irish towns (e.g., Worcester, York, Bandon) where butchers killed and prepared animals for consumption.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Fishamble Street, Dublin, was formerly a *fish-shambles*.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Sheffield had 183 slaughterhouses in 1910, and it was estimated that there were 20,000 in England and Wales.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The slaughterhouse emerged as a coherent institution in the 19th century.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] A combination of health and social concerns, exacerbated by the rapid urbanisation experienced during the Industrial Revolution, led social reformers to call for the isolation, sequester and regulation of animal slaughter.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] As a result of this tension, meat markets within the city were closed and abattoirs built outside city limits.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] An early framework for the establishment of public slaughterhouses was put in place in Paris in 1810, under the reign of the Emperor Napoleon.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Five areas were set aside on the outskirts of the city and the feudal privileges of the guilds were curtailed.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] As the meat requirements of the growing number of residents in London steadily expanded, the meat markets both within the city and beyond attracted increasing levels of public disapproval.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Meat had been traded at Smithfield Market as early as the 10th century.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] By 1726, it was regarded as "without question, the greatest in the world", by Daniel Defoe.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] By the middle of the 19th century, in the course of a single year 220,000 head of cattle and 1,500,000 sheep would be "violently forced into an area of five acres, in the very heart of London, through its narrowest and most crowded thoroughfares".
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] By the early 19th century, pamphlets were being circulated arguing in favor of the removal of the livestock market and its relocation outside of the city due to the extremely low hygienic conditions as well as the brutal treatment of the cattle.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In 1843, the *Farmer's Magazine* published a petition signed by bankers, salesmen, aldermen, butchers and local residents against the expansion of the livestock market.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The Town Police Clauses Act 1847 created a licensing and registration system, though few slaughter houses were closed.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] An Act of Parliament was eventually passed in 1852.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Under its provisions, a new cattle-market was constructed in Copenhagen Fields, Islington.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The new Metropolitan Cattle Market was also opened in 1855, and West Smithfield was left as waste ground for about a decade, until the construction of the new market began in the 1860s under the authority of the 1860 Metropolitan Meat and Poultry Market Act.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The market was designed by architect Sir Horace Jones and was completed in 1868.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] A cut and cover railway tunnel was constructed beneath the market to create a triangular junction with the railway between Blackfriars and King's Cross.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] This allowed animals to be transported into the slaughterhouse by train and the subsequent transfer of animal carcasses to the Cold Store building, or direct to the meat market via lifts.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] At the same time, the first large and centralized slaughterhouse in Paris was constructed in 1867 under the orders of Napoleon III at the Parc de la Villette and heavily influenced the subsequent development of the institution throughout Europe.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] These slaughterhouses were regulated by law to ensure good standards of hygiene, the prevention of the spread of disease and the minimization of needless animal cruelty.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The slaughterhouse had to be equipped with a specialized water supply system to effectively clean the operating area of blood and offal.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Veterinary scientists, notably George Fleming and John Gamgee, campaigned for stringent levels of inspection to ensure that epizootics such as rinderpest (a devastating outbreak of the disease covered all of Britain in 1865) would not be able to spread.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] By 1874, three meat inspectors were appointed for the London area, and the Public Health Act 1875 required local authorities to provide central slaughterhouses (they were only given powers to close unsanitary slaughterhouses in 1890).
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Yet the appointment of slaughterhouse inspectors and the establishment of centralised abattoirs took place much earlier in the British colonies, such as the colonies of New South Wales and Victoria, and in Scotland where 80% of cattle were slaughtered in public abattoirs by 1930.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In Victoria the *Melbourne Abattoirs Act 1850* (NSW) "confined the slaughtering of animals to prescribed public abattoirs, while at the same time prohibiting the killing of sheep, lamb, pigs or goats at any other place within the city limits".
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Animals were shipped alive to British ports from Ireland, from Europe and from the colonies and slaughtered in large abattoirs at the ports.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Attempts were also made throughout the British Empire to reform the practice of slaughter itself, as the methods used came under increasing criticism for causing undue pain to the animals.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The eminent physician, Benjamin Ward Richardson, spent many years in developing more humane methods of slaughter.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] He brought into use no fewer than fourteen possible anesthetics for use in the slaughterhouse and even experimented with the use of electric current at the Royal Polytechnic Institution.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] As early as 1853, he designed a lethal chamber that would gas animals to death relatively painlessly, and he founded the Model Abattoir Society in 1882 to investigate and campaign for humane methods of slaughter.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The invention of refrigeration and the expansion of transportation networks by sea and rail allowed for the safe exportation of meat around the world.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The Edinburgh abattoir, which was built in 1910, had well lit laboratories, hot and cold water, gas, microscopes and equipment for cultivating organisms.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The English 1924 Public Health (Meat) Regulations required notification of slaughter to enable inspection of carcasses and enabled inspected carcasses to be marked.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The development of slaughterhouses was linked with industrial expansion of by-products.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] By 1932 the British by-product industry was worth about £97 million a year, employing 310,000 people.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The Aberdeen slaughterhouse sent hooves to Lancashire to make glue, intestines to Glasgow for sausages and hides to the Midland tanneries.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In January 1940 the British government took over the 16,000 slaughterhouses and by 1942 there were only 779.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In the latter part of the 20th century, the layout and design of most U.S. slaughterhouses was influenced by the work of Temple Grandin.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] She suggested that reducing the stress of animals being led to slaughter may help slaughterhouse operators improve efficiency and profit.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In particular she applied an understanding of animal psychology to design pens and corrals which funnel a herd of animals arriving at a slaughterhouse into a single file ready for slaughter.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Her corrals employ long sweeping curves so that each animal is prevented from seeing what lies ahead and just concentrates on the hind quarters of the animal in front of it.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] This design – along with the design elements of solid sides, solid crowd gate, and reduced noise at the end point – work together to encourage animals forward in the chute and to not reverse direction.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Named the Modular Harvest System, or M.H.S., it received USDA approval in 2010.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The M.H.S. consists of three separate trailers: One for slaughtering, one for consumable body parts, and one for other body parts.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Preparation of individual cuts is done at a butchery or other meat preparation facility.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The standards and regulations governing slaughterhouses vary considerably around the world.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In many countries the slaughter of animals is regulated by custom and tradition rather than by law.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In the non-Western world, including the Arab world, the Indian sub-continent, etc., both forms of meat are available: one which is produced in modern mechanized slaughterhouses, and the other from local butcher shops.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In some communities animal slaughter and permitted species may be controlled by religious laws, most notably *halal* for Muslims and *kashrut* for Jewish communities.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] This can cause conflicts with national regulations when a slaughterhouse adhering to the rules of religious preparation is located in some Western countries.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In Jewish law, captive bolts and other methods of pre-slaughter paralysis are generally not permissible, due to it being forbidden for an animal to be stunned prior to slaughter.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Various halal food authorities have more recently permitted the use of a recently developed fail-safe system of head-only stunning where the shock is non-fatal, and where it is possible to reverse the procedure and revive the animal after the shock.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The use of electronarcosis and other methods of dulling the sensing has been approved by the Egyptian Fatwa Committee.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] This allows these entities to continue their religious techniques while keeping accordance to the national regulations.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In some societies, traditional cultural and religious aversion to slaughter led to prejudice against the people involved.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In Japan, where the ban on slaughter of livestock for food was lifted in the late 19th century, the newly found slaughter industry drew workers primarily from villages of *burakumin*, who traditionally worked in occupations relating to death (such as executioners and undertakers).
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In some parts of western Japan, prejudice faced by current and former residents of such areas (*burakumin* "hamlet people") is still a sensitive issue.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Because of this, even the Japanese word for "slaughter" (屠殺, *tosatsu*) is deemed politically incorrect by some pressure groups as its inclusion of the kanji for "kill" (殺) supposedly portrays those who practise it in a negative manner.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Some countries have laws that exclude specific animal species or grades of animal from being slaughtered for human consumption, especially those that are taboo food.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The former Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee suggested in 2004 introducing legislation banning the slaughter of cows throughout India, as Hinduism holds cows as sacred and considers their slaughter unthinkable and offensive.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] This was often opposed on grounds of religious freedom.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The slaughter of cows and the importation of beef into the nation of Nepal are strictly forbidden.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Refrigeration technology allowed meat from the slaughterhouse to be preserved for longer periods.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] This led to the concept of the slaughterhouse as a freezing works.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Freezing works are common in New Zealand, Australia and South Africa.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In countries where meat is exported for a substantial profit the freezing works were built near docks, or near transport infrastructure.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Mobile poultry processing units (MPPUs) follow the same principles, but typically require only one trailer and, in much of the United States, may legally operate under USDA exemptions not available to red meat processors.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Several MPPUs have been in operation since before 2010, under various models of operation and ownership.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Most countries have laws in regard to the treatment of animals in slaughterhouses.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In the United States, there is the Humane Slaughter Act of 1958, a law requiring that all swine, sheep, cattle, and horses be stunned unconscious with application of a stunning device by a trained person before being hoisted up on the line.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] There is some debate over the enforcement of this act.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] This act, like those in many countries, exempts slaughter in accordance to religious law, such as kosher shechita and dhabiha halal.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Most strict interpretations of kashrut require that the animal be fully sensible when its carotid artery is cut.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The novel *The Jungle* presented a fictionalized account of unsanitary conditions in slaughterhouses and the meatpacking industry during the 1800s.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] This led directly to an investigation commissioned directly by President Theodore Roosevelt, and to the passage of the Meat Inspection Act and the Pure Food and Drug Act of 1906, which established the Food and Drug Administration.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] A much larger body of regulation deals with the public health and worker safety regulation and inspection.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In 1997, Gail Eisnitz, chief investigator for the Humane Farming Association (HFA), released the book *Slaughterhouse*.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] It includes interviews of slaughterhouse workers in the U.S. who say that, because of the speed with which they are required to work, animals are routinely skinned while apparently alive and still blinking, kicking and shrieking.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Eisnitz argues that this is not only cruel to the animals but also dangerous for the human workers, as cows weighing several thousands of pounds thrashing around in pain are likely to kick out and debilitate anyone working near them.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] According to the HFA, Eiznitz interviewed slaughterhouse workers representing over two million hours of experience, who, without exception, told her that they have beaten, strangled, boiled and dismembered animals alive or have failed to report those who do.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The workers described the effects the violence has had on their personal lives, with several admitting to being physically abusive or taking to alcohol and other drugs.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The HFA alleges that workers are required to kill up to 1,100 hogs an hour and end up taking their frustration out on the animals.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Eisnitz interviewed one worker, who had worked in ten slaughterhouses, about pig production.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Animal rights activists, anti-speciesists, vegetarians and vegans are prominent critics of slaughterhouses and have created events such as the march to close all slaughterhouses to voice concerns about the conditions in slaughterhouses and ask for their abolition.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Some have argued that humane animal slaughter is impossible.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] American slaughterhouse workers are three times more likely to suffer serious injury than the average American worker.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] NPR reports that pig and cattle slaughterhouse workers are nearly seven times more likely to suffer repetitive strain injuries than average.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] *The Guardian* reports that on average there are two amputations a week involving slaughterhouse workers in the United States.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] On average, one employee of Tyson Foods, the largest meat producer in America, is injured and amputates a finger or limb per month.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] The Bureau of Investigative Journalism reported that over a period of six years, in the UK 78 slaughter workers lost fingers, parts of fingers or limbs, more than 800 workers had serious injuries, and at least 4,500 had to take more than three days off after accidents.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In a 2018 study in the Italian Journal of Food Safety, slaughterhouse workers are instructed to wear ear protectors to protect their hearing from the loud noises in the facility.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] A 2004 study in the *Journal of Occupational and Environmental Medicine* found that "excess risks were observed for mortality from all causes, all cancers, and lung cancer" in workers employed in the New Zealand meat processing industry.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Slaughterhouse workers have a higher prevalence rate of mental health distress, including anxiety, detachment, depression, emotional numbing, perpetrator trauma, psychosocial distress, and PTSD, violence-supportive attitudes, and an increased crime levels.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Slaughterhouse workers have adaptive and maladaptive strategies to cope with the workplace environment and associated stressors.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Working at slaughterhouses often leads to a high amount of psychological trauma.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Carrying out this action requires workers to disconnect from what they are doing and from the creature standing before them.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Starting in the 1980s, Cargill, Conagra Brands, Tyson Foods and other large food companies moved most slaughterhouse operations to rural areas of the Southern United States which were more hostile to unionization efforts.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] Slaughterhouses in the United States commonly illegally employ and exploit underage workers and undocumented immigrants.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In 2010, Human Rights Watch described slaughterhouse line work in the United States as a human rights crime.
[src:biotechnology/abattoir] In a report by Oxfam America, slaughterhouse workers were observed not being allowed breaks, were often required to wear diapers, and were paid below minimum wage.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:biotechnology/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is essentially unavoidable.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress affects animals, but plants are especially dependent, if not solely dependent, on environmental factors, so it is particularly constraining.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is the most harmful factor concerning the growth and productivity of crops worldwide.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Research has also shown that abiotic stressors are at their most harmful when they occur together, in combinations of abiotic stress factors.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] The most common of the stressors are the easiest for people to identify, but there are many other, less recognizable abiotic stress factors which affect environments constantly.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Lesser-known stressors generally occur on a smaller scale.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] They include: poor edaphic conditions like rock content and pH levels, high radiation, compaction, contamination, and other, highly specific conditions like rapid rehydration during seed germination.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress, as a natural part of every ecosystem, will affect organisms in a variety of ways.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Although these effects may be either beneficial or detrimental, the location of the area is crucial in determining the extent of the impact that abiotic stress will have.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] The higher the latitude of the area affected, the greater the impact of abiotic stress will be on that area.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] So, a taiga or boreal forest is at the mercy of whatever abiotic stress factors may come along, while tropical zones are much less susceptible to such stressors.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] While abiotic stress may have negative impacts on individual organisms, there are cases where abiotic stress plays an important role in maintaining a healthy ecosystem.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Important ecosystem mechanisms and improved overall stress tolerance may rely on occasional low levels of abiotic stress.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] One example of a situation where abiotic stress plays a constructive role in an ecosystem is in natural wildfires.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Smaller fires are useful in reducing the overall fuel load of an area of forest or prairie.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] By clearing out dead brush and other organic matter, the risk of catastrophic and widespread fire decreases, and the residual ash of smaller fires helps add nutrients back into the soil.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] The observed benefits of these smaller and more controlled fires on land usability and species populations have led to the use of prescribed burning by humans for centuries.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Varying perspectives on the benefits and risks of fire to ecosystems have influenced official policy through history.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Forest Service, initially focused on fire control, changed its policy to one of fire management in 1974, recognizing these fires as a natural part of an ecosystem.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] There is also evidence that a diverse fire history between patches of land within an area has been shown to benefit transitional landscapes between savanna and forest.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Even though it is healthy for an ecosystem, a wildfire can still be considered an abiotic stressor, because it puts stress on individual organisms within the area.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] On the larger scale, though, natural wildfires are positive manifestations of abiotic stress.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] What also needs to be taken into account when looking for benefits of abiotic stress, is that one phenomenon may not affect an entire ecosystem in the same way.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] While a flood will kill most plants living low on the ground in a certain area, if there is rice there, it will thrive in the wet conditions.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Another example of this is in phytoplankton and zooplankton.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] The same types of conditions are usually considered stressful for these two types of organisms.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] They act very similarly when exposed to ultraviolet light and most toxins, but at elevated temperatures the phytoplankton reacts negatively, while the thermophilic zooplankton reacts positively to the increase in temperature.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] The two may be living in the same environment, but an increase in temperature of the area would prove stressful only for one of the organisms.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Lastly, abiotic stress has enabled species to grow, develop, and evolve, through the process of natural selection.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Heritable traits that improve an organism's resiliency under stressed conditions increase the likelihood that the organism will survive and reproduce, enabling it to pass these traits to the next generation.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Both plants and animals have evolved mechanisms allowing them to survive extremes.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] One of the detriments concerning abiotic stress involves farming.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] It has been claimed by one study that abiotic stress causes the most crop loss of any other factor and that most major crops are reduced in their yield by more than 50% from their potential yield.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Because abiotic stress is widely considered a detrimental effect, the research on this branch of the issue is extensive.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] For more information on the harmful effects of abiotic stress, see the sections below on plants and animals.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] A plant's first line of defense against abiotic stress is in its roots.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] If the soil holding the plant is healthy and biologically diverse, the plant will have a higher chance of surviving stressful conditions.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] The plant responses to stress are dependent on the tissue or organ affected by the stress.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] For example, transcriptional responses to stress are tissue or cell specific in roots and are quite different depending on the stress involved.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] One of the primary responses to abiotic stress such as high salinity is the disruption of the Na+/K+ ratio in the cytoplasm of the plant cell.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] High concentrations of Na+, for example, can decrease the capacity for the plant to take up water and also alter enzyme and transporter functions.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Evolved adaptations to efficiently restore cellular ion homeostasis have led to a wide variety of stress tolerant plants.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Facilitation, or the positive interactions between different species of plants, is an intricate web of association in a natural environment.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] In areas of high stress, the level of facilitation is especially high as well.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] This could possibly be because the plants need a stronger network to survive in a harsher environment, so their interactions between species, such as cross-pollination or mutualistic actions, become more common to cope with the severity of their habitat.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Plants also adapt very differently from one another, even from a plant living in the same area.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] When a group of different plant species was prompted by a variety of different stress signals, such as drought or cold, each plant responded uniquely.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Hardly any of the responses were similar, even though the plants had become accustomed to exactly the same home environment.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Serpentine soils (media with low concentrations of nutrients and high concentrations of heavy metals) can be a source of abiotic stress.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Initially, the absorption of toxic metal ions is limited by cell membrane exclusion.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Ions that are absorbed into tissues are sequestered in cell vacuoles.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] This sequestration mechanism is facilitated by proteins on the vacuole membrane.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] An example of plants that adapt to serpentine soil are Metallophytes, or hyperaccumulators, as they are known for their ability to absorbed heavy metals using the root-to-shoot translocation (which it will absorb into shoots rather than the plant itself).
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] They're also extinguished for their ability to absorb toxic substances from heavy metals.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Chemical priming has been proposed to increase tolerance to abiotic stresses in crop plants.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] In this method, which is analogous to vaccination, stress-inducing chemical agents are introduced to the plant in brief doses so that the plant begins preparing defense mechanisms.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Thus, when the abiotic stress occurs, the plant has already prepared defense mechanisms that can be activated faster and increase tolerance.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress mostly affects plants used in agriculture.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Some examples of adverse conditions (which may be caused by climate change) are high or low temperatures, drought, salinity, and toxins.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Elevated global temperatures present a severe bottleneck for crop yields, as heat stress alters membrane fluidity, accelerates destructive transpiration rates, and heavily impairs a plant's overall Water Use Efficiency (WUE).
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] When crops encounter extreme thermal environments during early reproductive or vegetative stages, cellular homeostasis is broken down, causing grain yield reduction and premature leaf senescence.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] To mitigate down-stream damage from overlapping thermal and drought shocks, advanced ex-ante strategies such as physical seed priming or chemical priming agents are applied.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] These priming interventions activate early molecular, enzymatic, and hormonal pre-defense responses within the seed tissue, enabling the plant to maintain higher functional stability and lower oxidative injury when heat stress occurs later in the field environment.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Flooding acts as a compound environmental stressor that is broadly categorized into waterlogging (where only the root system is inundated) and complete submergence (where the entire plant is covered by water).
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] The primary hazard of flooding is gas diffusion restriction, which triggers oxygen starvation (hypoxia or anoxia) in the rhizosphere and alters essential plant hormone signaling networks, such as the regulation between Sub1A and non-Sub1A genotypes in rice.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] To cope with complete submergence, tolerant plants rely on distinct physiological survival strategies.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Furthermore, monitoring maximum quantum yield performance reveals that preserving photosynthetic efficiency during transient flooding stress is paramount to driving rapid physiological recovery once the water recedes.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Soil acidity acts as a sweeping abiotic stress factor on global arable lands, primarily because low pH environments trigger dangerous chemical toxicities dominated by soluble aluminum (Al3+ )and iron, which structurally damage root anatomy and limit basic development.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] High acidity also locks up vital macronutrients, causing severe phosphorus starvation stress that forces plants to aggressively modify their lateral root structures to maximize surface area absorption.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] To remediate heavy-metal-polluted and highly acidic substrates, bioremediation utilizes hyperaccumulator plant traits (metallophytes).
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] These specialized plants successfully survive the toxicity of acidic media by relying on a highly developed root-to-shoot translocation system, which efficiently absorbs and transports toxic ions away from fragile root tissues and sequesters them safely inside the upper shoot vacuoles.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Soil salinization, the accumulation of water-soluble salts to levels that negatively impact plant production, is a global phenomenon affecting approximately 831 million hectares of land.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] More specifically, the phenomenon threatens 19.5% of the world's irrigated agricultural land and 2.1% of the world's non-irrigated (dry-land) agricultural lands.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] High soil salinity content can be harmful to plants because water-soluble salts can alter osmotic potential gradients and consequently inhibit many cellular functions.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Over generations, many plants have mutated and built different mechanisms to counter salinity effects.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] A good combatant of salinity in plants is the hormone ethylene.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Ethylene is known for regulating plant growth and development and dealing with stress conditions.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Many central membrane proteins in plants, such as ETO2, ERS1 and EIN2, are used for ethylene signaling in many plant growth processes.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Mutations in these proteins can lead to heightened salt sensitivity and can limit plant growth.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] The effects of salinity has been studied on *Arabidopsis* plants that have mutated ERS1, ERS2, ETR1, ETR2 and EIN4 proteins.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] These proteins are used for ethylene signaling against certain stress conditions, such as salt and the ethylene precursor ACC is used to suppress any sensitivity to the salt stress.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus (P) is an essential macronutrient required for plant growth and development, but it is present only in limited quantities in most of the world's soil.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Plants use P mainly in the form of soluble inorganic phosphates (PO4−−−) but are subject to abiotic stress when there is not enough soluble PO4−−− in the soil.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus forms insoluble complexes with Ca and Mg in alkaline soils and with Al and Fe in acidic soils that make the phosphorus unavailable for plant roots.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] It has been shown that PHR1, a MYB-related transcription factor, is a master regulator of P-starvation response in plants.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Drought stress, defined as naturally occurring water deficit, is a main cause of crop losses in agriculture.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] This is because water is essential for many fundamental processes in plant growth.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] It has become especially important in recent years to find a way to combat drought stress.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] A decrease in precipitation and consequent increase in drought are extremely likely in the future due to an increase in global warming.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Plants have come up with many mechanisms and adaptations to try and deal with drought stress.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] One of the leading ways that plants combat drought stress is by closing their stomata.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] A key hormone regulating stomatal opening and closing is abscisic acid (ABA).
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Synthesis of ABA causes the ABA to bind to receptors.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] This binding then affects the opening of ion channels, thereby decreasing turgor pressure in the stomata and causing them to close.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Recent studies by Gonzalez-Villagra, et al., have shown how ABA levels increased in drought-stressed plants (2018).
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] They showed that when plants were placed in a stressful situation, they produced more ABA to try to conserve any water they had in their leaves.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Another extremely important factor in dealing with drought stress and regulating the uptake and export of water is aquaporins (AQPs).
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] AQPs are integral membrane proteins that make up channels.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] These channels' main job is the transport of water and other essential solutes.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] AQPs are both transcriptionally and post-transcriptionally regulated by many different factors such as ABA, GA3, pH and Ca2+; and the specific levels of AQPs in certain parts of the plant, such as roots or leaves, helps to draw as much water into the plant as possible.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] By understanding the mechanisms of both AQPs and the hormone ABA, scientists will be better able to produce drought-resistant plants in the future.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] A study by Tombesi et al., found that plants which had previously been exposed to drought were able to minimize water loss and decrease water use.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] They found that plants which were exposed to drought conditions actually changed the way they regulated their stomata and what they called "hydraulic safety margin" so as to decrease the vulnerability of the plant.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] By changing the regulation of stomata and subsequently the transpiration, plants were able to function better when less water was available.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] For animals, the most stressful of all the abiotic stressors is heat.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] This is because many species are unable to regulate their internal body temperature.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Even in the species that are able to regulate their own temperature, it is not always a completely accurate system.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Temperature determines metabolic rates, heart rates, and other very important factors within the bodies of animals, so an extreme temperature change can easily distress the animal's body.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Animals can respond to extreme heat, for example, through natural heat acclimation or by burrowing into the ground to find a cooler space.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] It is also possible to see in animals that a high genetic diversity is beneficial in providing resiliency against harsh abiotic stressors.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] This acts as a sort of stock room when a species is plagued by the perils of natural selection.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] A variety of galling insects are among the most specialized and diverse herbivores on the planet, and their extensive protections against abiotic stress factors have helped the insect in gaining that position of honor.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Biodiversity is determined by many things, and one of them is abiotic stress.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] If an environment is highly stressful, biodiversity tends to be low.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] If abiotic stress does not have a strong presence in an area, the biodiversity will be much higher.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] This idea leads into the understanding of how abiotic stress and endangered species are related.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] It has been observed through a variety of environments that as the level of abiotic stress increases, the number of species decreases.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] This means that species are more likely to become population threatened, endangered, and even extinct, when and where abiotic stress is especially harsh.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Data suggests that anthropogenic activity has increased the global temperature, and likely increased the odds of extreme climate events such as drought, fire conditions and flooding.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] Threats to organisms and ecosystem biodiversity due to increased abiotic stress are one major impact of this change.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] The effects of climate change on biomes vary due to the location, patterns of precipitation, and the organisms which inhabit them.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] On the species level, the increased abiotic stress due to climate change can lead to adaptations which increase a species' reproductive success under these conditions.
[src:biotechnology/abiotic-stress] However, such highly specialized adaptations may leave species vulnerable to other stresses.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone is miscible with water and serves as an important organic solvent in industry, home, and laboratory.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] About 6.7 million tonnes were produced worldwide in 2010, mainly for use as a solvent and for production of methyl methacrylate and bisphenol A, which are precursors to widely used plastics.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] It is a common building block in organic chemistry.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] It serves as a solvent in household products such as nail polish remover and paint thinner.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] It has volatile organic compound (VOC)-exempt status in the United States.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone is produced and disposed of in the human body through normal metabolic processes.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Small quantities of it are present naturally in blood and urine.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] People with diabetic ketoacidosis produce it in larger amounts.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Medical ketogenic diets that increase ketone bodies (acetone, β-hydroxybutyric acid and acetoacetic acid) in the blood are used to suppress epileptic attacks in children with treatment-resistant epilepsy.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] From the 17th century, and before modern developments in organic chemistry nomenclature, acetone was given many different names.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] They included "spirit of Saturn", which was given when it was thought to be a compound of lead and, later, "pyro-acetic spirit" and "pyro-acetic ester".
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Prior to the name "acetone" being coined by French chemists, it was named "mesit" (from the Greek μεσίτης, meaning mediator) by Carl Reichenbach, who also said that methyl alcohol consisted of mesit and ethyl alcohol.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Names derived from mesit include mesitylene and mesityl oxide which were first synthesised from acetone.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] In 1839, the name "acetone" began to be used, because it was obtained from acetic acid.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Unlike many compounds with the *acet-* prefix which have a 2-carbon chain, acetone has a 3-carbon chain.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] That has caused confusion because there can not be a ketone with 2 carbons.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] The prefix refers to acetone's relation to vinegar (*acetum* in Latin, also the source of the words "acid" and "acetic"), rather than its chemical structure.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone was first produced by Andreas Libavius in 1606 by distillation of lead(II) acetate.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] In 1832, French chemist Jean-Baptiste Dumas and German chemist Justus von Liebig determined the empirical formula for acetone.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] In 1833, French chemists Antoine Bussy and Michel Chevreul decided to name acetone by adding the suffix *-one* to the stem of the corresponding acid (viz, acetic acid) just as a similarly prepared product of what was then confused with margaric acid was named margarone.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] By 1852, Alexander William Williamson, an English chemist, realized that acetone was methyl acetyl; the following year, the French chemist Charles Frédéric Gerhardt concurred.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] In 1865, a German chemist, August Kekulé published the modern structural formula for acetone.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Johann Josef Loschmidt had presented the structure of acetone in 1861, but his privately published booklet received little attention.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] During World War I, Chaim Weizmann developed the biochemical process for industrial production of acetone (Weizmann Process).
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone is produced directly or indirectly from propene.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Approximately 83% of acetone is produced via the cumene process; as a result, acetone production is tied to phenol production.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Other processes involve the direct oxidation of propylene (Wacker-Hoechst process), or the hydration of propylene to give 2-propanol, which is oxidized (dehydrogenated) to acetone.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Previously, acetone was produced by the dry distillation of acetates, for example calcium acetate in ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] After that time during World War I, acetone was produced using acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation with *Clostridium acetobutylicum* bacteria, which was developed by Chaim Weizmann (later the first president of Israel) in order to help the British war effort, in the preparation of Cordite.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] This acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation was eventually abandoned when newer methods with better yields were found.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] In 2010, the worldwide production capacity for acetone was estimated at 6.7 million tonnes per year.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] With 1.56 million tonnes per year, the United States had the highest production capacity, followed by Taiwan and China.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] The largest producer of acetone is INEOS Phenol, owning 17% of the world's capacity, with also significant capacity (7–8%) by Mitsui, Sunoco and Shell in 2010.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] INEOS Phenol also owns the world's largest production site (420,000 tonnes/annum) in Beveren, Belgium.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] The spot price of acetone in summer 2011 was 1100–1250 USD/tonne in the United States.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Humans exhale several milligrams of acetone per day and it arises from the decarboxylation of acetoacetate.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Small amounts of acetone are produced in the body by the decarboxylation of ketone bodies.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Certain dietary patterns including prolonged fasting and high-fat low-carbohydrate dieting, can produce ketosis, in which acetone is formed in body tissue.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Certain health conditions, such as alcoholism and diabetes, can produce ketoacidosis, uncontrollable ketosis that leads to a sharp, and potentially fatal, increase in the acidity of the blood.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Since it is a byproduct of fermentation, acetone is a byproduct of the distillery industry.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] It is produced by terrestrial vegetation, undefined ocean processes, incomplete combustion of biomass, or oxidation of hydrocarbons in the atmosphere.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Like most ketones, acetone exhibits the keto–enol tautomerism in which the nominal keto structure (CH3)2C=O of acetone itself is in equilibrium with the enol isomer (CH3)C(OH)=(CH2) (**prop-1-en-2-ol**).
[src:biotechnology/acetone] In acetone vapor at ambient temperature, only 2.4×10−7% of the molecules are in the enol form.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] In the presence of suitable catalysts, two acetone molecules also combine to form the compound diacetone alcohol (CH3)C=O(CH2)C(OH)(CH3)2, which on dehydration gives mesityl oxide (CH3)C=O(CH)=C(CH3)2.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] This product can further combine with another acetone molecule, with loss of another molecule of water, yielding phorone and other compounds.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone is a weak Lewis base that forms adducts with soft acids like I2 and hard acids like phenol.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone also forms complexes with divalent metals.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Under ultraviolet light, acetone fluoresces.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] The flame temperature of pure acetone is 1980 °C.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] At its melting point (−96 °C) is claimed to polymerize to give a white elastic solid, soluble in acetone, stable for several hours at room temperature.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] To do so, a vapor of acetone is co-condensed with magnesium as a catalyst onto a very cold surface.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] The outcome of irradiation of acetone is wavelength dependent.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] The latter process is relevant to the atmospheric chemistry of acetone.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone can then be metabolized either by CYP2E1 via methylglyoxal to D-lactate and pyruvate, and ultimately glucose/energy, or by a different pathway via propylene glycol to pyruvate, lactate, acetate (usable for energy) and propionaldehyde.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] About a third of the world's acetone is used as a solvent, and a quarter is consumed as acetone cyanohydrin, a precursor to methyl methacrylate.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone is used to synthesize methyl methacrylate.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] The third major use of acetone (about 20%) is synthesizing bisphenol A.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Bisphenol A is a component of many polymers such as polycarbonates, polyurethanes, and epoxy resins.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Many millions of kilograms of acetone are consumed in the production of the solvents methyl isobutyl alcohol and methyl isobutyl ketone.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] These products arise via an initial aldol condensation to give diacetone alcohol.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Condensation with acetylene gives 2-methylbut-3-yn-2-ol, precursor to synthetic terpenes and terpenoids.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone is a good solvent for many plastics and some synthetic fibers.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] It is used for thinning polyester resin, cleaning tools used with it, and dissolving two-part epoxies and superglue before they harden.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] It is used as one of the volatile components of some paints and varnishes.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Although itself flammable, acetone is used extensively as a solvent for the safe transportation and storage of acetylene, which cannot be safely pressurized as a pure compound.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Vessels containing a porous material are first filled with acetone followed by acetylene, which dissolves into the acetone.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] One litre of acetone can dissolve around 250 litres of acetylene at a pressure of 10 bars (1.0 MPa).
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone is used as a solvent by the pharmaceutical industry and as a denaturant in denatured alcohol.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone is also present as an excipient in some pharmaceutical drugs.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] A variety of organic reactions employ acetone as a polar, aprotic solvent, e.g. the Jones oxidation.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Because acetone is cheap, volatile, and dissolves or decomposes with most laboratory chemicals, an acetone rinse is the standard technique to remove solid residues from laboratory glassware before a final wash.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Despite common desiccatory use, acetone dries only via bulk displacement and dilution.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] It forms no azeotropes with water (see azeotrope tables).
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone also removes certain stains from microscope slides.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] An acetone/dry ice mixture cools many low-temperature reactions.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Make-up artists use acetone to remove skin adhesive from the netting of wigs and mustaches by immersing the item in an acetone bath, then removing the softened glue residue with a stiff brush.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone is a main ingredient in many nail polish removers because it breaks down nail polish.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] It is used for all types of nail polish removal, like gel nail polish, dip powder and acrylic nails.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] The chemical modifies peptides, both at α- or ε-amino groups, and in a poorly understood but rapid modification of certain glycine residues.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] In pathology, acetone helps find lymph nodes in fatty tissues (such as the mesentery) for tumor staging.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] The liquid dissolves the fat and hardens the nodes, making them easier to find.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Dermatologists use acetone with alcohol for acne treatments to chemically peel dry skin.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Common agents used for chemical peeling are salicylic acid, glycolic acid, azelaic acid, 30% salicylic acid in ethanol, and trichloroacetic acid (TCA).
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Prior to chemexfoliation, the skin is cleaned and excess fat removed in a process called defatting, using acetone, hexachlorophene, or a combination of these agents.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone has been shown to have anticonvulsant effects in animal models of epilepsy, in the absence of toxicity, when administered in millimolar concentrations.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] It has been hypothesized that the high-fat low-carbohydrate ketogenic diet used clinically to control drug-resistant epilepsy in children works by elevating acetone in the brain.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Because of their higher energy requirements, children have higher acetone production than most adults – and the younger the child, the higher the expected production.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] This indicates that children are not uniquely susceptible to acetone exposure.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] External exposures are small compared to the exposures associated with the ketogenic diet.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone has a relatively long lifetime in the atmosphere of about 2 weeks.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Because of its long lifetime, it can be transported by atmospheric winds to the upper troposphere and lower stratosphere where it can influence hydrogen radical (HOx) production and ozone (O3) levels.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] These two peroxy radicals can then undergo a series of reactions to produce hydrogen oxide radicals (HOx) and can therefore have a significant impact on atmospheric chemistry including concentration of ozone (O3) in the upper troposphere.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Photolysis is just one possible processes that removes acetone from the atmosphere.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone can also be removed by ocean processes and by deposition to dry land surfaces.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] The contributions of each sink to the removal of acetone from the atmosphere is still not fully understood.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone's most hazardous property is its extreme flammability.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] In small amounts, acetone burns with a dull blue flame; in larger amounts, fuel evaporation causes incomplete combustion and a bright yellow flame.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] When above acetone's flash point of −20 °C (−4 °F), air mixtures of 2.5‑12.8% acetone (by volume) may explode or cause a flash fire.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Vapors can flow along surfaces to distant ignition sources and flash back.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Static discharge may ignite acetone vapors, though acetone has a very high ignition initiation energy and accidental ignition is rare.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone's auto-ignition temperature is relatively high 465 °C (869 °F); moreover, auto-ignition temperature depends upon experimental conditions, such as exposure time, and has been quoted as high as 535 °C.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Even pouring or spraying acetone over red-glowing coal will not ignite it, due to the high vapour concentration and the cooling effect of evaporation.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone should be stored away from strong oxidizers, such as concentrated nitric and sulfuric acid mixtures.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] It may explode when stored with chloroform in the presence of a base.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] When oxidized without combustion, for example with hydrogen peroxide, acetone may form acetone peroxide, a highly unstable primary explosive.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone peroxide may be formed accidentally, e.g. when waste peroxide is poured into waste solvents.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone occurs naturally as part of certain metabolic processes in the human body, and has been studied extensively and is believed to exhibit only slight toxicity in normal use.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] There is no strong evidence of chronic health effects if basic precautions are followed.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] It is generally recognized to have low acute and chronic toxicity if ingested and/or inhaled.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone is not regarded as a carcinogen, a mutagen, or a concern for chronic neurotoxicity effects.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone can be found as an ingredient in a variety of consumer products ranging from cosmetics to processed and unprocessed foods.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] The United States Food and Drug Administration rates acetone as a generally recognized as safe (GRAS) substance when present in food and drink at concentrations from 5 to 8 mg/L.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acetone is an irritant, causing mild skin and moderate-to-severe eye irritation.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Like many other solvents, acetone may depress the central nervous system at high vapor concentrations.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] Acute toxicity for mice by ingestion (LD50) is 3 g/kg, and by inhalation (LC50) is 44 g/m3 over 4 hours.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] In 1995, the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) removed acetone from the list of volatile organic compounds.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] In making its decision EPA conducted an extensive review of the available toxicity data on acetone, which was continued through the 2000s.
[src:biotechnology/acetone] It found that the evaluable "data are inadequate for an assessment of the human carcinogenic potential of acetone".
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] In biology, **adaptation** has three related meanings.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Firstly, it is the dynamic evolutionary process of natural selection that fits organisms to their environment, enhancing their evolutionary fitness.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Secondly, it is a state reached by the population during that process.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Thirdly, it is a phenotypic trait or **adaptive trait**, with a functional role in each individual organism, that is maintained and has evolved through natural selection.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Historically, adaptation has been described from the time of the ancient Greek philosophers such as Empedocles and Aristotle.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] In 18th and 19th-century natural theology, adaptation was taken as evidence for the existence of a deity.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Charles Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace proposed instead that it was explained by natural selection.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Adaptation is related to biological fitness, which governs the rate of evolution as measured by changes in allele frequencies.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Often, two or more species co-adapt and co-evolve as they develop adaptations that interlock with those of the other species, such as with flowering plants and pollinating insects.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] In mimicry, species evolve to resemble other species; in mimicry this is a mutually beneficial co-evolution as each of a group of strongly defended species (such as wasps able to sting) come to advertise their defences in the same way.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Features evolved for one purpose may be co-opted for a different one, as when the insulating feathers of dinosaurs were co-opted for bird flight.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Adaptation is a major topic in the philosophy of biology, as it concerns function and purpose (teleology).
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Some biologists try to avoid terms which imply purpose in adaptation, not least because they suggest a deity's intentions, but others note that adaptation is necessarily purposeful.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Adaptation is an observable fact of life accepted by philosophers and natural historians from ancient times, independently of their views on evolution, but their explanations differed.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Empedocles did not believe that adaptation required a final cause (a purpose), but thought that it "came about naturally, since such things survived." Aristotle did believe in final causes, but assumed that species were fixed.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] In natural theology, adaptation was interpreted as the work of a deity and as evidence for the existence of God.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] William Paley believed that organisms were perfectly adapted to the lives they led, an argument that shadowed Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, who had argued that God had brought about "the best of all possible worlds." Voltaire's satire Dr.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Pangloss is a parody of this optimistic idea, and David Hume also argued against design.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Charles Darwin broke with the tradition by emphasising the flaws and limitations which occurred in the animal and plant worlds.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Jean-Baptiste Lamarck proposed a tendency for organisms to become more complex, moving up a ladder of progress, plus "the influence of circumstances", usually expressed as *use and disuse*.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] This second, subsidiary element of his theory is what is now called Lamarckism, a proto-evolutionary hypothesis of the inheritance of acquired characteristics, intended to explain adaptations by natural means.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Other natural historians, such as Buffon, accepted adaptation, and some also accepted evolution, without voicing their opinions as to the mechanism.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] This illustrates the real merit of Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace, and secondary figures such as Henry Walter Bates, for putting forward a mechanism whose significance had only been glimpsed previously.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] A century later, experimental field studies and breeding experiments by people such as E.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Ford and Theodosius Dobzhansky produced evidence that natural selection was not only the 'engine' behind adaptation, but was a much stronger force than had previously been thought.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Adaptation is primarily a process rather than a physical form or part of a body.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] An internal parasite (such as a liver fluke) can illustrate the distinction: such a parasite may have a very simple bodily structure, but nevertheless the organism is highly adapted to its specific environment.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] From this we see that adaptation is not just a matter of visible traits: in such parasites critical adaptations take place in the life cycle, which is often quite complex.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] However, as a practical term, "adaptation" often refers to a *product*: those features of a species which result from the process.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Many aspects of an animal or plant can be correctly called adaptations, though there are always some features whose function remains in doubt.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] By using the term *adaptation* for the evolutionary *process*, and *adaptive trait* for the bodily part or function (the product), one may distinguish the two different senses of the word.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Adaptation is one of the two main processes that explain the observed diversity of species, such as the different species of Darwin's finches.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The other process is speciation, in which new species arise, typically through reproductive isolation.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] An example widely used today to study the interplay of adaptation and speciation is the evolution of cichlid fish in African lakes, where the question of reproductive isolation is complex.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Adaptation is not always a simple matter where the ideal phenotype evolves for a given environment.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] An organism must be viable at all stages of its development and at all stages of its evolution.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] This places *constraints* on the evolution of development, behaviour, and structure of organisms.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The main constraint, over which there has been much debate, is the requirement that each genetic and phenotypic change during evolution should be relatively small, because developmental systems are so complex and interlinked.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] However, it is not clear what "relatively small" should mean, for example polyploidy in plants is a reasonably common large genetic change.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The origin of eukaryotic endosymbiosis is a more dramatic example.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] All adaptations help organisms survive in their ecological niches.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The adaptive traits may be structural, behavioural or physiological.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Structural adaptations are physical features of an organism, such as shape, body covering, armament, and internal organization.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Behavioural adaptations are inherited systems of behaviour, whether inherited in detail as instincts, or as a neuropsychological capacity for learning.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Examples include searching for food, mating, and vocalizations.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Physiological adaptations permit the organism to perform special functions such as making venom, secreting slime, and phototropism, but also involve more general functions such as growth and development, temperature regulation, ionic balance and other aspects of homeostasis.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Adaptation affects all aspects of the life of an organism.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] is the state of being adapted: the degree to which an organism is able to live and reproduce in a given set of habitats.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] is an aspect of the developmental pattern of the organism which enables or enhances the probability of that organism surviving and reproducing.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Adaptation differs from flexibility, acclimatization, and learning, all of which are changes during life which are not inherited.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Flexibility deals with the relative capacity of an organism to maintain itself in different habitats: its degree of specialization.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Acclimatization describes automatic physiological adjustments during life; learning means alteration in behavioural performance during life.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Flexibility stems from phenotypic plasticity, the ability of an organism with a given genotype (genetic type) to change its phenotype (observable characteristics) in response to changes in its habitat, or to move to a different habitat.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The degree of flexibility is inherited, and varies between individuals.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] A highly specialized animal or plant lives only in a well-defined habitat, eats a specific type of food, and cannot survive if its needs are not met.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Many herbivores are like this; extreme examples are koalas which depend on *Eucalyptus*, and giant pandas which require bamboo.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] A generalist, on the other hand, eats a range of food, and can survive in many different conditions.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Examples are humans, rats, crabs and many carnivores.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The *tendency* to behave in a specialized or exploratory manner is inherited—it is an adaptation.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Rather different is developmental flexibility: "An animal or plant is developmentally flexible if when it is raised in or transferred to new conditions, it changes in structure so that it is better fitted to survive in the new environment," writes the evolutionary biologist John Maynard Smith.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] If humans move to a higher altitude, respiration and physical exertion become a problem, but after spending time in high altitude conditions they acclimatize to the reduced partial pressure of oxygen, such as by producing more red blood cells.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The ability to acclimatize is an adaptation, but the acclimatization itself is not.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The reproductive rate declines, but deaths from some tropical diseases also go down.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Over a longer period of time, some people are better able to reproduce at high altitudes than others.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] They contribute more heavily to later generations, and gradually by natural selection the whole population becomes adapted to the new conditions.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] This has demonstrably occurred, as the observed performance of long-term communities at higher altitude is significantly better than the performance of new arrivals, even when the new arrivals have had time to acclimatize.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] There is a relationship between adaptedness and the concept of fitness used in population genetics.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Differences in fitness between genotypes predict the rate of evolution by natural selection.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Natural selection changes the relative frequencies of alternative phenotypes, insofar as they are heritable.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] However, a phenotype with high adaptedness may not have high fitness.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Dobzhansky mentioned the example of the Californian redwood, which is highly adapted, but a relict species in danger of extinction.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Elliott Sober commented that adaptation was a retrospective concept since it implied something about the history of a trait, whereas fitness predicts a trait's future.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The absolute contribution to the next generation by a genotype or a class of genotypes.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] when applied to the population as a whole.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The extent to which a phenotype fits its local ecological niche.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Sewall Wright proposed that populations occupy *adaptive peaks* on a fitness landscape.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] To evolve to another, higher peak, a population would first have to pass through a valley of maladaptive intermediate stages, and might be "trapped" on a peak that is not optimally adapted.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Before Darwin, adaptation was seen as a fixed relationship between an organism and its habitat.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] It was not appreciated that as the climate changed, so did the habitat; and as the habitat changed, so did the biota.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Also, habitats are subject to changes in their biota: for example, invasions of species from other areas.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The relative numbers of species in a given habitat are always changing.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Change is the rule, though much depends on the speed and degree of the change.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] When the habitat changes, three main things may happen to a resident population: habitat tracking, genetic change or extinction.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] In fact, all three things may occur in sequence.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Of these three effects only genetic change brings about adaptation.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] When a habitat changes, the resident population typically moves to more suitable places; this is the typical response of flying insects or oceanic organisms, which have wide (though not unlimited) opportunity for movement.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] This common response is called *habitat tracking*.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] It is one explanation put forward for the periods of apparent stasis in the fossil record (the punctuated equilibrium theory).
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Without mutation, the ultimate source of all genetic variation, there would be no genetic changes and no subsequent adaptation through evolution by natural selection.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Genetic change occurs in a population when mutation increases or decreases in its initial frequency followed by random genetic drift, migration, recombination or natural selection act on this genetic variation.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] One example is that the first pathways of enzyme-based metabolism at the very origin of life on Earth may have been co-opted components of the already-existing purine nucleotide metabolism, a metabolic pathway that evolved in an ancient RNA world.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The co-option requires new mutations and through natural selection, the population then adapts genetically to its present circumstances.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Genetic changes may result in entirely new or gradual change to visible structures, or they may adjust physiological activity in a way that suits the habitat.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The varying shapes of the beaks of Darwin's finches, for example, are driven by adaptive mutations in the ALX1 gene.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The coat color of different wild mouse species matches their environments, whether black lava or light sand, owing to adaptive mutations in the melanocortin 1 receptor and other melanin pathway genes.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Physiological resistance to the heart poisons (cardiac glycosides) that monarch butterflies store in their bodies to protect themselves from predators are driven by adaptive mutations in the target of the poison, the sodium pump, resulting in target site insensitivity.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] These same adaptive mutations and similar changes at the same amino acid sites were found to evolve in a parallel manner in distantly related insects that feed on the same plants, and even in a bird that feeds on monarchs through convergent evolution, a hallmark of adaptation.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Convergence at the gene-level across distantly related species can arise because of evolutionary constraint.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Habitats and biota do frequently change over time and space.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Therefore, it follows that the process of adaptation is never fully complete.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Over time, it may happen that the environment changes little, and the species comes to fit its surroundings better and better, resulting in stabilizing selection.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] On the other hand, it may happen that changes in the environment occur suddenly, and then the species becomes less and less well adapted.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The only way for it to climb back up that fitness peak is via the introduction of new genetic variation for natural selection to act upon.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Seen like this, adaptation is a genetic *tracking process*, which goes on all the time to some extent, but especially when the population cannot or does not move to another, less hostile area.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Given enough genetic change, as well as specific demographic conditions, an adaptation may be enough to bring a population back from the brink of extinction in a process called evolutionary rescue.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Adaptation does affect, to some extent, every species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Leigh Van Valen thought that even in a stable environment, because of antagonistic species interactions and limited resources, a species must constantly had to adapt to maintain its relative standing.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] This became known as the Red Queen hypothesis, as seen in host-parasite interactions.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Existing genetic variation and mutation were the traditional sources of material on which natural selection could act.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] In addition, horizontal gene transfer is possible between organisms in different species, using mechanisms as varied as gene cassettes, plasmids, transposons and viruses such as bacteriophages.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] In coevolution, where the existence of one species is tightly bound up with the life of another species, new or 'improved' adaptations which occur in one species are often followed by the appearance and spread of corresponding features in the other species.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] In other words, each species triggers reciprocal natural selection in the other.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] These co-adaptational relationships are intrinsically dynamic, and may continue on a trajectory for millions of years, as has occurred in the relationship between flowering plants and pollinating insects.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Bates' work on Amazonian butterflies led him to develop the first scientific account of mimicry, especially the kind of mimicry which bears his name: Batesian mimicry.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] This is the mimicry by a palatable species of an unpalatable or noxious species (the model), gaining a selective advantage as predators avoid the model and therefore also the mimic.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Mimicry is thus an anti-predator adaptation.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] A common example seen in temperate gardens is the hoverfly (Syrphidae), many of which—though bearing no sting—mimic the warning coloration of aculeate Hymenoptera (wasps and bees).
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Such mimicry does not need to be perfect to improve the survival of the palatable species.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Bates, Wallace and Fritz Müller believed that Batesian and Müllerian mimicry provided evidence for the action of natural selection, a view which is now standard amongst biologists.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] All adaptations have a downside: horse legs are great for running on grass, but they cannot scratch their backs; mammals' hair helps temperature, but offers a niche for ectoparasites; the only flying penguins do is under water.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Adaptations serving different functions may be mutually destructive.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Compromise and makeshift occur widely, not perfection.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Selection pressures pull in different directions, and the adaptation that results is some kind of compromise.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Consider the antlers of the Irish elk, (often supposed to be far too large; in deer antler size has an allometric relationship to body size).
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Antlers serve positively for defence against predators, and to score victories in the annual rut.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] But they are costly in terms of resources.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Their size during the last glacial period presumably depended on the relative gain and loss of reproductive capacity in the population of elks during that time.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] As another example, camouflage to avoid detection is destroyed when vivid coloration is displayed at mating time.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Here the risk to life is counterbalanced by the necessity for reproduction.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Stream-dwelling salamanders, such as Caucasian salamander or Gold-striped salamander have very slender, long bodies, perfectly adapted to life at the banks of fast small rivers and mountain brooks.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Elongated body protects their larvae from being washed out by current.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] However, elongated body increases risk of desiccation and decreases dispersal ability of the salamanders; it also negatively affects their fecundity.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] As a result, fire salamander, less perfectly adapted to the mountain brook habitats, is in general more successful, have a higher fecundity and broader geographic range.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The peacock's ornamental train (grown anew in time for each mating season) is a famous adaptation.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] It must reduce his maneuverability and flight, and is hugely conspicuous; also, its growth costs food resources.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The recognition of sexual selection was for a long time in abeyance, but has been rehabilitated.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The conflict between the size of the human foetal brain at birth, (which cannot be larger than about 400 cm3, else it will not get through the mother's pelvis) and the size needed for an adult brain (about 1400 cm3), means the brain of a newborn child is quite immature.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The most vital things in human life (locomotion, speech) just have to wait while the brain grows and matures.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] That is the result of the birth compromise.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Much of the problem comes from our upright bipedal stance, without which our pelvis could be shaped more suitably for birth.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] As another example, the long neck of a giraffe brings benefits but at a cost.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The neck of a giraffe can be up to 2 m (6 ft 7 in) in length.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The benefits are that it can be used for inter-species competition or for foraging on tall trees where shorter herbivores cannot reach.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The cost is that a long neck is heavy and adds to the animal's body mass, requiring additional energy to build the neck and to carry its weight around.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Pre-adaptation occurs when a population has characteristics which by chance are suited for a set of conditions not previously experienced.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] For example, the polyploid cordgrass *Spartina townsendii* is better adapted than either of its parent species to their own habitat of saline marsh and mud-flats.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Among domestic animals, the White Leghorn chicken is markedly more resistant to vitamin B1 deficiency than other breeds; on a plentiful diet this makes no difference, but on a restricted diet this preadaptation could be decisive.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Pre-adaptation may arise because a natural population carries a huge quantity of genetic variability.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] In diploid eukaryotes, this is a consequence of the system of sexual reproduction, where mutant alleles get partially shielded, for example, by genetic dominance.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Microorganisms, with their huge populations, also carry a great deal of genetic variability.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The word is controversial because it is teleological and the entire concept of natural selection depends on the presence of genetic variation, regardless of the population size of a species in question.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Features that now appear as adaptations sometimes arose by co-option of existing traits, evolved for some other purpose.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The classic example is the ear ossicles of mammals, which we know from paleontological and embryological evidence originated in the upper and lower jaws and the hyoid bone of their synapsid ancestors, and further back still were part of the gill arches of early fish.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The word *exaptation* was coined to cover these common evolutionary shifts in function.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The flight feathers of birds evolved from the much earlier feathers of dinosaurs, which might have been used for insulation or for display.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Animals including earthworms, beavers and humans use some of their adaptations to modify their surroundings, so as to maximize their chances of surviving and reproducing.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Beavers create dams and lodges, changing the ecosystems of the valleys around them.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Earthworms, as Darwin noted, improve the topsoil in which they live by incorporating organic matter.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Humans have constructed extensive civilizations with cities in environments as varied as the Arctic and hot deserts.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] In all three cases, the construction and maintenance of ecological niches helps drive the continued selection of the genes of these animals, in an environment that the animals have modified.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Some traits do not appear to be adaptive as they have a neutral or deleterious effect on fitness in the current environment.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Another possibility is that a trait may have been adaptive at some point in an organism's evolutionary history, but a change in habitats caused what used to be an adaptation to become unnecessary or even maladapted.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Many organisms have vestigial organs, which are the remnants of fully functional structures in their ancestors.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] As a result of changes in lifestyle the organs became redundant, and are either not functional or reduced in functionality.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Since any structure represents some kind of cost to the general economy of the body, an advantage may accrue from their elimination once they are not functional.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Examples: wisdom teeth in humans; the loss of pigment and functional eyes in cave fauna; the loss of structure in endoparasites.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] If a population cannot move or change sufficiently to preserve its long-term viability, then it will become extinct, at least in that locale.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The species may or may not survive in other locales.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Species extinction occurs when the death rate over the entire species exceeds the birth rate for a long enough period for the species to disappear.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] It was an observation of Van Valen that groups of species tend to have a characteristic and fairly regular rate of extinction.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The first stage in the evolution of life on earth is often hypothesized to be the RNA world in which short self-replicating RNA molecules proliferated before the evolution of DNA and proteins.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] By this hypothesis, life started when RNA chains began to self-replicate, initiating the three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation of type, and competition for resources.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The fitness of an RNA replicator (its per capita rate of increase) would likely have been a function of its intrinsic adaptive capacities, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and the availability of resources.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The three primary adaptive capacities may have been: (1) replication with moderate fidelity, giving rise to heritability while allowing variation of type, (2) resistance to decay, and (3) acquisition of resources.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] These adaptive capacities would have been determined by the folded configurations of the RNA replicators resulting from their nucleotide sequences.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] In his biology, Aristotle introduced teleology to describe the adaptedness of organisms, but without accepting the supernatural intention built into Plato's thinking, which Aristotle rejected.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] Modern biologists continue to face the same difficulty.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] On the one hand, adaptation is purposeful: natural selection chooses what works and eliminates what does not.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] On the other hand, biologists by and large reject conscious purpose in evolution.
[src:biotechnology/adaptation] The dilemma gave rise to a famous joke by the evolutionary biologist Haldane: "Teleology is like a mistress to a biologist: he cannot live without her but he's unwilling to be seen with her in public.'" David Hull commented that Haldane's mistress "has become a lawfully wedded wife.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] An **adverse effect** is an undesired harmful effect resulting from a medication or other intervention, such as surgery.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] An adverse effect may be termed a "side effect", when judged to be secondary to a main or therapeutic effect.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] The term complication is similar to adverse effect, but the latter is typically used in pharmacological contexts, or when the negative effect is expected or common.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] If the negative effect results from an unsuitable or incorrect dosage or procedure, this is called a medical error and not an adverse effect.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Adverse effects are sometimes referred to as "iatrogenic" because they are generated by a physician/treatment.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Some adverse effects occur only when starting, increasing or discontinuing a treatment.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Using a drug or other medical intervention which is contraindicated may increase the risk of adverse effects.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Adverse effects may cause complications of a disease or procedure and negatively affect its prognosis.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] They may also lead to non-compliance with a treatment regimen.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Adverse effects of medical treatment resulted in 142,000 deaths in 2013 up from 94,000 deaths in 1990 globally.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] The harmful outcome is usually indicated by some result such as morbidity, mortality, alteration in body weight, levels of enzymes, loss of function, or as a pathological change detected at the microscopic, macroscopic or physiological level.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] It may also be indicated by symptoms reported by a patient.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Adverse effects may cause a reversible or irreversible change, including an increase or decrease in the susceptibility of the individual to other chemicals, foods, or procedures, such as drug interactions.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] In clinical trials, a distinction is made between an adverse event and a serious adverse event.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Generally, any event which causes death, permanent damage, birth defects, or requires hospitalization is considered a serious adverse event.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] The results of trials are often included in the labelling of the medication to provide information both for patients and the prescribing physicians.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] The term "life-threatening" in the context of a serious adverse event refers to an event in which the patient was at risk of death at the time of the event; it does not refer to an event which hypothetically might have caused death if it were more severe.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] In many countries, adverse effects are required by law to be reported, researched in clinical trials and included into the patient information accompanying medical devices and drugs for sale to the public.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Investigators in human clinical trials are obligated to report these events in clinical study reports.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Research suggests that these events are often inadequately reported in publicly available reports.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Because of the lack of these data and uncertainty about methods for synthesising them, individuals conducting systematic reviews and meta-analyses of therapeutic interventions often unknowingly overemphasise health benefit.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] To balance the overemphasis on benefit, scholars have called for more complete reporting of harm from clinical trials.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] The Yellow Card Scheme is a United Kingdom initiative run by the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) and the Commission on Human Medicines (CHM) to gather information on adverse effects to medicines.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] This includes all licensed medicines, from medicines issued on prescription to medicines bought over the counter from a supermarket.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] The scheme also includes all herbal supplements and unlicensed medicines found in cosmetic treatments.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Adverse drug reactions (ADRs) can be reported by a number of health care professionals including physicians, pharmacists and nurses, as well as patients.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] In the United States several reporting systems have been built, such as the Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS), the Manufacturer and User Facility Device Experience Database (MAUDE) and the Special Nutritionals Adverse Event Monitoring System.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] MedWatch is the main reporting center, operated by the Food and Drug Administration.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] In Australia, adverse effect reporting is administered by the Adverse Drug Reactions Advisory Committee (ADRAC), a subcommittee of the Australian Drug Evaluation Committee (ADEC).
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Reporting is voluntary, and ADRAC requests healthcare professionals to report all adverse reactions to its current drugs of interest, and serious adverse reactions to any drug.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] ADRAC publishes the Australian Adverse Drug Reactions Bulletin every two months.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] The Government's Quality Use of Medicines program is tasked with acting on this reporting to reduce and minimize the number of preventable adverse effects each year.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Adverse reaction reporting is an important component of New Zealand's pharmacovigilance activities.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] The Centre for Adverse Reactions Monitoring (CARM) in Dunedin is New Zealand's national monitoring centre for adverse reactions.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] It collects and evaluates spontaneous reports of adverse reactions to medicines, vaccines, herbal products and dietary supplements from health professionals in New Zealand.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] In Canada, adverse reaction reporting is an important component of the surveillance of marketed health products conducted by the Health Products and Food Branch (HPFB) of Health Canada.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Within HPFB, the Marketed Health Products Directorate leads the coordination and implementation of consistent monitoring practices with regards to assessment of signals and safety trends, and risk communications concerning regulated marketed health products.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] MHPD also works closely with international organizations to facilitate the sharing of information.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Adverse reaction reporting is mandatory for the industry and voluntary for consumers and health professionals.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] In principle, medical professionals are required to report all adverse effects related to a specific form of therapy.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] In practice, it is at the discretion of the professional to determine whether a medical event is at all related to the therapy.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] As a result, routine adverse effects reporting often may not include long-term and subtle effects that may ultimately be attributed to a therapy.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Part of the difficulty is identifying the source of a complaint.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] A headache in a patient taking medication for influenza may be caused by the underlying disease or may be an adverse effect of the treatment.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] In patients with end-stage cancer, death is a very likely outcome and whether the drug is the cause or a bystander is often difficult to discern.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Surgery may have a number of undesirable or harmful effects, such as infection, hemorrhage, inflammation, scarring, loss of function, or changes in local blood flow.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] They can be reversible or irreversible, and a compromise must be found by the physician and the patient between the beneficial or life-saving consequences of surgery versus its adverse effects.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] For example, a limb may be lost to amputation in case of untreatable gangrene, but the patient's life is saved.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Presently, one of the greatest advantages of minimally invasive surgery, such as laparoscopic surgery, is the reduction of adverse effects.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Other nonsurgical physical procedures, such as high-intensity radiation therapy, may cause burns and alterations in the skin.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] In general, these therapies try to avoid damage to healthy tissues while maximizing the therapeutic effect.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Vaccination may have adverse effects due to the nature of its biological preparation, sometimes using attenuated pathogens and toxins.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Common adverse effects may be fever, malaise and local reactions in the vaccination site.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Very rarely, there is a serious adverse effect, such as eczema vaccinatum, a severe, sometimes fatal complication which may result in persons who have eczema or atopic dermatitis.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Diagnostic procedures may also have adverse effects, depending much on whether they are invasive, minimally invasive or noninvasive.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] For example, allergic reactions to radiocontrast materials often occur, and a colonoscopy may cause the perforation of the intestinal wall.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Adverse effects can occur as a collateral or side effect of many interventions, but they are particularly important in pharmacology, due to its wider, and sometimes uncontrollable, use by way of self-medication.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Thus, responsible drug use becomes an important issue here.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Adverse effects, like therapeutic effects of drugs, are a function of dosage or drug levels at the target organs, so they may be avoided or decreased by means of careful and precise pharmacokinetics, the change of drug levels in the organism in function of time after administration.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Adverse effects may also be caused by drug interaction.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] This often occurs when patients fail to inform their physician and pharmacist of all the medications they are taking, including herbal and dietary supplements.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] The new medication may interact agonistically or antagonistically (potentiate or decrease the intended therapeutic effect), causing significant morbidity and mortality around the world.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Drug-drug and food-drug interactions may occur, and so-called "natural drugs" used in alternative medicine can have dangerous adverse effects.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] The scientific field of activity associated with drug safety is increasingly government-regulated, and is of major concern for the public, as well as to drug manufacturers.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] The distinction between adverse and nonadverse effects is a major undertaking when a new drug is developed and tested before marketing it.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] This is done in toxicity studies to determine the nonadverse effect level (NOAEL).
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] These studies are used to define the dosage to be used in human testing (phase I), as well as to calculate the maximum admissible daily intake.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Most drugs have a large list of nonsevere or mild adverse effects which do not rule out continued usage.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] These effects, which have a widely variable incidence according to individual sensitivity, include nausea, dizziness, diarrhea, malaise, vomiting, headache, dermatitis, dry mouth, etc.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] These can be considered a form of pseudo-allergic reaction, as not all users experience these effects; many users experience none at all.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] The Medication Appropriateness Tool for Comorbid Health Conditions in Dementia (MATCH-D) warns that people with dementia are more likely to experience adverse effects, and that they are less likely to be able to reliably report symptoms.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Sometimes, putative medical adverse effects are regarded as controversial and generate heated discussions in society and lawsuits against drug manufacturers.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] One example is the controversy as to whether autism was linked to the MMR vaccine (or to thiomersal, a mercury-based preservative used in some vaccines).
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] The alleged correlation has been widely discredited by a large number studies, and despite removal of thimerosal from most early childhood vaccines beginning with those manufactured in 2003, the rate of autism has not decreased as would be expected if it had been the causative agent.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] Another instance is the potential adverse effects of silicone breast implants, which led to class actions brought by tens of thousands of plaintiffs against manufacturers of gel-based implants, due to allegations of damage to the immune system which have not yet been conclusively proven.
[src:biotechnology/adverse-effect-medicine] In 1998, Dow Corning settled its remaining suits for $3.2 Billion and went into bankruptcy.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The term *biotechnology* was first used by Károly Ereky in 1919 to refer to the production of products from raw materials with the aid of living organisms.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The core principle of biotechnology involves harnessing biological systems and organisms, such as bacteria, yeast, and plants, to perform specific tasks or produce valuable substances.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology has had a significant impact on many areas of society, from medicine to agriculture to environmental science.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] One of the key techniques used in biotechnology is genetic engineering, which allows scientists to modify the genetic makeup of organisms to achieve desired outcomes.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] This can involve inserting genes from one organism into another, and consequently, creating new traits or modifying existing ones.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Other important techniques used in biotechnology include tissue culture, which allows researchers to grow cells and tissues in the lab for research and medical purposes, and fermentation, which is used to produce a wide range of products such as beer, wine, and cheese.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The applications of biotechnology are diverse and have led to the development of products like drugs, biofuels, genetically modified crops, and innovative materials.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] It has also been used to address environmental challenges, such as developing biodegradable plastics and using microorganisms to clean up contaminated sites.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] As a result, there is ongoing debate and regulation surrounding the use and application of biotechnology in various industries and fields.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology encompasses a wide range of procedures for modifying living organisms for human purposes, going back to domestication of animals, the cultivation of plants, and "improvements" to these through breeding programs that employ artificial selection and hybridization.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Modern usage also includes genetic engineering, as well as cell and tissue culture technologies.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The American Chemical Society defines *biotechnology* as the application of biological organisms, systems, or processes by various industries to learning about the science of life and the improvement of the value of materials and organisms, such as pharmaceuticals, crops, and livestock.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] As per the European Federation of Biotechnology, biotechnology is the integration of natural science and organisms, cells, parts thereof, and molecular analogues for products and services.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology is based on the basic biological sciences (e.g., molecular biology, biochemistry, cell biology, embryology, genetics, microbiology) and conversely provides methods to support and perform basic research in biology.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The utilization of biological processes, organisms or systems to produce products that are anticipated to improve human lives is termed biotechnology.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] By contrast, bioengineering is generally thought of as a related field that more heavily emphasizes higher systems approaches (not necessarily the altering or using of biological materials *directly*) for interfacing with and utilizing living things.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Bioengineering is the application of the principles of engineering and natural sciences to tissues, cells, and molecules.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] This can be considered as the use of knowledge from working with and manipulating biology to achieve a result that can improve functions in plants and animals.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Relatedly, biomedical engineering is an overlapping field that often draws upon and applies *biotechnology* (by various definitions), especially in certain sub-fields of biomedical or chemical engineering such as tissue engineering, biopharmaceutical engineering, and genetic engineering.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Many forms of human-derived agriculture fit the broad definition of "utilizing a biotechnological system to make products".
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The cultivation of plants may be viewed as the earliest biotechnological enterprise.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Agriculture has been theorized to have become the dominant way of producing food since the Neolithic Revolution.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Through early biotechnology, the earliest farmers selected and bred the best-suited crops (e.g., those with the highest yields) to produce enough food to support a growing population.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] As crops and fields became increasingly large and difficult to maintain, it was discovered that specific organisms and their by-products could effectively fertilize, restore nitrogen, and control pests.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Throughout the history of agriculture, farmers have inadvertently altered the genetics of their crops through introducing them to new environments and breeding them with other plants — one of the first forms of biotechnology.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] These processes were also included in the early fermentation of beer.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] These processes were introduced in early Mesopotamia, Egypt, China and India, and still use the same basic biological methods.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] In brewing, malted grains (containing enzymes) convert starch from grains into sugar and then adding specific yeasts to produce beer.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] In this process, carbohydrates in the grains broke down into alcohols, such as ethanol.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Later, other cultures developed the process of lactic acid fermentation, which produced other preserved foods, such as soy sauce.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Fermentation was also used in this time period to produce leavened bread.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Although the process of fermentation was not fully understood until Louis Pasteur's work in 1857, it is still the first use of biotechnology to convert a food source into another form.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Before the time of Charles Darwin's work and life, animal and plant scientists had already used selective breeding.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Darwin added to that body of work with his scientific observations about the ability of science to change species.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] These accounts contributed to Darwin's theory of natural selection.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] For thousands of years, humans have used selective breeding to improve the production of crops and livestock to use them for food.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] In selective breeding, organisms with desirable characteristics are mated to produce offspring with the same characteristics.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] For example, this technique was used with corn to produce the largest and sweetest crops.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] In the early twentieth century scientists gained a greater understanding of microbiology and explored ways of manufacturing specific products.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] In 1917, Chaim Weizmann first used a pure microbiological culture in an industrial process, that of manufacturing corn starch using *Clostridium acetobutylicum,* to produce acetone, which the United Kingdom desperately needed to manufacture explosives during World War I.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology has also led to the development of antibiotics.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] In 1928, Alexander Fleming discovered the mold *Penicillium*.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] His work led to the purification of the antibiotic formed by the mold by Howard Florey, Ernst Boris Chain and Norman Heatley – to form what we today know as penicillin.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] In 1940, penicillin became available for medicinal use to treat bacterial infections in humans.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The field of modern biotechnology is generally thought of as having been born in 1971 when Paul Berg's (Stanford) experiments in gene splicing had early success.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Cohen (Stanford) significantly advanced the new technology in 1972 by transferring genetic material into a bacterium, such that the imported material would be reproduced.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The commercial viability of a biotechnology industry was significantly expanded on June 16, 1980, when the United States Supreme Court ruled that a genetically modified microorganism could be patented in the case of *Diamond v.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Indian-born Ananda Chakrabarty, working for General Electric, had modified a bacterium (of the genus *Pseudomonas*) capable of breaking down crude oil, which he proposed to use in treating oil spills.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] (Chakrabarty's work did not involve gene manipulation but rather the transfer of entire organelles between strains of the *Pseudomonas* bacterium).
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The MOSFET was invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960, Two years later, Leland C.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Clark and Champ Lyons invented the first biosensor in 1962.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Biosensor MOSFETs were later developed, and they have since been widely used to measure physical, chemical, biological and environmental parameters.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The first BioFET was the ion-sensitive field-effect transistor (ISFET), invented by Piet Bergveld in 1970.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] It is a special type of MOSFET, where the metal gate is replaced by an ion-sensitive membrane, electrolyte solution and reference electrode.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The ISFET is widely used in biomedical applications, such as the detection of DNA hybridization, biomarker detection from blood, antibody detection, glucose measurement, pH sensing, and genetic technology.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] By the mid-1980s, other BioFETs had been developed, including the gas sensor FET (GASFET), pressure sensor FET (PRESSFET), chemical field-effect transistor (ChemFET), reference ISFET (REFET), enzyme-modified FET (ENFET) and immunologically modified FET (IMFET).
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] By the early 2000s, BioFETs such as the DNA field-effect transistor (DNAFET), gene-modified FET (GenFET) and cell-potential BioFET (CPFET) had been developed.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] A factor influencing the biotechnology sector's success is improved intellectual property rights legislation—and enforcement—worldwide, as well as strengthened demand for medical and pharmaceutical products.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Rising demand for biofuels is expected to be good news for the biotechnology sector, with the Department of Energy estimating ethanol usage could reduce U.S. petroleum-derived fuel consumption by up to 30% by 2030.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The biotechnology sector has allowed the U.S. farming industry to rapidly increase its supply of corn and soybeans—the main inputs into biofuels—by developing genetically modified seeds that resist pests and drought.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] By increasing farm productivity, biotechnology boosts biofuel production.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology has applications in four major industrial areas, including health care (medical), crop production and agriculture, non-food (industrial) uses of crops and other products (e.g., biodegradable plastics, vegetable oil, biofuels), and environmental uses.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] For example, one application of biotechnology is the directed use of microorganisms for the manufacture of organic products (examples include beer and milk products).
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Another example is using naturally present bacteria by the mining industry in bioleaching.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology is also used to recycle, treat waste, clean up sites contaminated by industrial activities (bioremediation), and also to produce biological weapons.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] In medicine, modern biotechnology has many applications in areas such as pharmaceutical drug discoveries and production, pharmacogenomics, and genetic testing (or genetic screening).
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] In 2021, nearly 40% of the total company value of pharmaceutical biotech companies worldwide were active in Oncology with Neurology and Rare Diseases being the other two big applications.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Pharmacogenomics (a combination of pharmacology and genomics) is the technology that analyses how genetic makeup affects an individual's response to drugs.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Researchers in the field investigate the influence of genetic variation on drug responses in patients by correlating gene expression or single-nucleotide polymorphisms with a drug's efficacy or toxicity.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The purpose of pharmacogenomics is to develop rational means to optimize drug therapy, with respect to the patients' genotype, to ensure maximum efficacy with minimal adverse effects.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Such approaches promise the advent of "personalized medicine"; in which drugs and drug combinations are optimized for each individual's unique genetic makeup.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology has contributed to the discovery and manufacturing of traditional small molecule pharmaceutical drugs as well as drugs that are the product of biotechnology – biopharmaceutics.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Modern biotechnology can be used to manufacture existing medicines relatively easily and cheaply.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The first genetically engineered products were medicines designed to treat human diseases.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] To cite one example, in 1978 Genentech developed synthetic humanized insulin by joining its gene with a plasmid vector inserted into the bacterium *Escherichia coli*.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Insulin, widely used for the treatment of diabetes, was previously extracted from the pancreas of abattoir animals (cattle or pigs).
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The genetically engineered bacteria are able to produce large quantities of synthetic human insulin at relatively low cost.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology has also enabled emerging therapeutics like gene therapy.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Genetic testing allows the genetic diagnosis of vulnerabilities to inherited diseases, and can also be used to determine a child's parentage (genetic mother and father) or in general a person's ancestry.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] In addition to studying chromosomes to the level of individual genes, genetic testing in a broader sense includes biochemical tests for the possible presence of genetic diseases, or mutant forms of genes associated with increased risk of developing genetic disorders.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Genetic testing identifies changes in chromosomes, genes, or proteins.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Most of the time, testing is used to find changes that are associated with inherited disorders.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The results of a genetic test can confirm or rule out a suspected genetic condition or help determine a person's chance of developing or passing on a genetic disorder.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] As of 2011 several hundred genetic tests were in use.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Since genetic testing may open up ethical or psychological problems, genetic testing is often accompanied by genetic counseling.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Genetically modified crops ("GM crops", or "biotech crops") are plants used in agriculture, the DNA of which has been modified with genetic engineering techniques.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] In most cases, the main aim is to introduce a new trait that does not occur naturally in the species.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology firms can contribute to future food security by improving the nutrition and viability of urban agriculture.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Furthermore, the protection of intellectual property rights encourages private sector investment in agrobiotechnology.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Examples in food crops include resistance to certain pests, diseases, stressful environmental conditions, resistance to chemical treatments (e.g. resistance to a herbicide), reduction of spoilage, or improving the nutrient profile of the crop.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Examples in non-food crops include production of pharmaceutical agents, biofuels, and other industrially useful goods, as well as for bioremediation.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Farmers have widely adopted GM technology.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Between 1996 and 2011, the total surface area of land cultivated with GM crops had increased by a factor of 94, from 17,000 to 1,600,000 square kilometers (4,200,000 to 395,400,000 acres).
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] 10% of the world's crop lands were planted with GM crops in 2010.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] As of 2011, 11 different transgenic crops were grown commercially on 395 million acres (160 million hectares) in 29 countries such as the US, Brazil, Argentina, India, Canada, China, Paraguay, Pakistan, South Africa, Uruguay, Bolivia, Australia, Philippines, Myanmar, Burkina Faso, Mexico, and Spain.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Genetically modified foods are foods produced from organisms that have had specific changes introduced into their DNA with the methods of genetic engineering.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] These techniques have allowed for the introduction of new crop traits as well as a far greater control over a food's genetic structure than previously afforded by methods such as selective breeding and mutation breeding.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Commercial sale of genetically modified foods began in 1994, when Calgene first marketed its Flavr Savr delayed ripening tomato.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] To date most genetic modification of foods have primarily focused on cash crops in high demand by farmers such as soybean, corn, canola, and cotton seed oil.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] These have been engineered for resistance to pathogens and herbicides and better nutrient profiles.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] GM livestock have also been experimentally developed; in November 2013 none were available on the market, but in 2015 the FDA approved the first GM salmon for commercial production and consumption.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] There is a scientific consensus that currently available food derived from GM crops poses no greater risk to human health than conventional food, but that each GM food needs to be tested on a case-by-case basis before introduction.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Nonetheless, members of the public are much less likely than scientists to perceive GM foods as safe.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The legal and regulatory status of GM foods varies by country, with some nations banning or restricting them, and others permitting them with widely differing degrees of regulation.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] GM crops also provide a number of ecological benefits, if not used in excess.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Insect-resistant crops have proven to lower pesticide usage, therefore reducing the environmental impact of pesticides as a whole.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology has several applications in the realm of food security.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Crops like Golden rice are engineered to have higher nutritional content, and there is potential for food products with longer shelf lives.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Though not a form of agricultural biotechnology, vaccines can help prevent diseases found in animal agriculture.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Additionally, agricultural biotechnology can expedite breeding processes in order to yield faster results and provide greater quantities of food.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Transgenic biofortification in cereals has been considered as a promising method to combat malnutrition in India and other countries.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Industrial biotechnology (known mainly in Europe as white biotechnology) is the application of biotechnology for industrial purposes, including industrial fermentation.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] It includes the practice of using cells such as microorganisms, or components of cells like enzymes, to generate industrially useful products in sectors such as chemicals, food and feed, detergents, paper and pulp, textiles and biofuels.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] In the current decades, significant progress has been done in creating genetically modified organisms (GMOs) that enhance the diversity of applications and economical viability of industrial biotechnology.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] By using renewable raw materials to produce a variety of chemicals and fuels, industrial biotechnology is actively advancing towards lowering greenhouse gas emissions and moving away from a petrochemical-based economy.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Synthetic biology is considered one of the essential cornerstones in industrial biotechnology due to its financial and sustainable contribution to the manufacturing sector.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Jointly biotechnology and synthetic biology play a crucial role in generating cost-effective products with nature-friendly features by using bio-based production instead of fossil-based.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Synthetic biology can be used to engineer model microorganisms, such as *Escherichia coli*, by genome editing tools to enhance their ability to produce bio-based products, such as bioproduction of medicines and biofuels.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] For instance, *E. coli* and *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* in a consortium could be used as industrial microbes to produce precursors of the chemotherapeutic agent paclitaxel by applying the metabolic engineering in a co-culture approach to exploit the benefits from the two microbes.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Another example of synthetic biology applications in industrial biotechnology is the re-engineering of the metabolic pathways of *E. coli* by CRISPR and CRISPRi systems toward the production of a chemical known as 1,4-butanediol, which is used in fiber manufacturing.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] In order to produce 1,4-butanediol, the authors alter the metabolic regulation of the *Escherichia coli* by CRISPR to induce point mutation in the *glt*A gene, knockout of the *sad* gene, and knock-in six genes (*cat*1, *suc*D, *4hbd*, *cat*2, *bld*, and *bdh*).
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Whereas CRISPRi system used to knockdown the three competing genes (*gab*D, *ybg*C, and *tes*B) that affect the biosynthesis pathway of 1,4-butanediol.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Consequently, the yield of 1,4-butanediol significantly increased from 0.9 to 1.8 g/L.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Environmental biotechnology includes various disciplines that play an essential role in reducing environmental waste and providing environmentally safe processes, such as biofiltration and biodegradation.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The environment can be affected by biotechnologies, both positively and adversely.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Cleaning up environmental wastes is an example of an application of environmental biotechnology; whereas loss of biodiversity or loss of containment of a harmful microbe are examples of environmental implications of biotechnology.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Many cities have installed CityTrees, which use biotechnology to filter pollutants from urban atmospheres.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] There are differences in the regulation of GMOs between countries, with some of the most marked differences occurring between the US and Europe.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Regulation varies in a given country depending on the intended use of the products of the genetic engineering.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] For example, a crop not intended for food use is generally not reviewed by authorities responsible for food safety.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The European Union differentiates between approval for cultivation within the EU and approval for import and processing.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] While only a few GMOs have been approved for cultivation in the EU a number of GMOs have been approved for import and processing.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The cultivation of GMOs has triggered a debate about the coexistence of GM and non-GM crops.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Depending on the coexistence regulations, incentives for the cultivation of GM crops differ.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] The EUginius (European GMO Initiative for a Unified Database System) database is intended to help companies, interested private users and competent authorities to find precise information on the presence, detection and identification of GMOs used in the European Union.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] In 1988, after prompting from the United States Congress, the National Institute of General Medical Sciences (National Institutes of Health) (NIGMS) instituted a funding mechanism for biotechnology training.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Universities nationwide compete for these funds to establish Biotechnology Training Programs (BTPs).
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Each successful application is generally funded for five years then must be competitively renewed.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Graduate students in turn compete for acceptance into a BTP; if accepted, then stipend, tuition and health insurance support are provided for two or three years during the course of their PhD thesis work.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Nineteen institutions offer NIGMS supported BTPs.
[src:biotechnology/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology training is also offered at undergraduate level and in community colleges.
